      {
        "user": "How does \"transformer (architecture)\" differ from MoE (Mixture of Experts)?",
        "assistant": "A **Transformer** and a **Mixture of Experts (MoE)** are not exactly the same kind of thing.\n\nA **Transformer** is a neural network architecture for processing sequences using **self-attention** and feed-forward layers.\n\nA **Mixture of Experts** is a model design technique where different parts of the input are routed to different specialized subnetworks called **experts**.\n\nIn practice, many modern MoE models are actually **MoE Transformers**.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\nA **Transformer** describes the overall architecture: attention layers, feed-forward layers, residual connections, positional information, etc.\n\nAn **MoE** describes how some computation is distributed across multiple expert networks.\n\nSo:\n\n> Transformer = an architecture for modeling sequences  \n> MoE = a way to scale parts of a model by using multiple specialized experts\n\n---\n\n## Standard Transformer: dense computation\n\nIn a regular Transformer, every token usually passes through the same layers.\n\nFor example, in a Transformer block:\n\n1. Self-attention\n2. Feed-forward network\n3. Layer normalization and residual connections\n\nEvery token uses the same feed-forward network.\n\nThis is called **dense** computation because the whole relevant part of the model is used for each token.\n\n---\n\n## MoE: routed expert computation\n\nIn a Mixture of Experts model, some layers contain multiple expert networks.\n\nInstead of sending every token through the same feed-forward network, a **router** or **gating network** decides which expert or experts should process each token.\n\nFor example:\n\n> token → router → Expert 3 and Expert 7 → output\n\nUsually, only a small number of experts are activated per token, such as the top 1 or top 2 experts.\n\nThis is called **sparse** computation.\n\n---\n\n## Key differences\n\n| Feature | Transformer | MoE |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | Neural network architecture | Scaling/routing technique |\n| Main mechanism | Self-attention + feed-forward layers | Router selects expert networks |\n| Computation | Usually dense | Often sparse |\n| Token processing | Same layers for all tokens | Different tokens may use different experts |\n| Purpose | Model relationships in sequences | Increase model capacity efficiently |\n| Can they be combined? | Yes | Often used inside Transformers |\n| Examples | BERT, GPT, T5 | Switch Transformer, GShard, Mixtral, some large LLMs |\n\n---\n\n## Important point: MoE often lives inside a Transformer\n\nA common MoE Transformer block looks like this:\n\n1. Self-attention layer\n2. MoE feed-forward layer\n3. Residual connections and normalization\n\nThe attention part may remain standard Transformer attention.\n\nThe usual feed-forward network is replaced with several experts plus a router.\n\nSo instead of:\n\n> attention → one feed-forward network\n\nyou get:\n\n> attention → router → selected expert feed-forward networks\n\n---\n\n## Why use MoE?\n\nMoE is useful because it increases the number of model parameters without increasing compute as much.\n\nFor example, a model may have many experts, but each token only uses a few of them.\n\nSo the model can have huge total capacity, while the cost per token stays relatively manageable.\n\nThis gives a rough tradeoff:\n\n> More parameters, but not proportionally more computation.\n\n---\n\n## Example\n\nImagine a language model with experts that specialize loosely in different kinds of text:\n\n- code\n- math\n- legal text\n- dialogue\n- scientific writing\n- different languages\n\nWhen a token comes in, the router chooses which expert or experts should handle it.\n\nThis specialization is not always clean or human-interpretable, but it is the basic idea.\n\n---\n\n## Tradeoffs of MoE\n\nMoE models can be powerful, but they are more complex to train and deploy.\n\nChallenges include:\n\n- routing instability\n- load balancing across experts\n- communication overhead across devices\n- making sure some experts do not get overused\n- harder inference infrastructure\n\nA dense Transformer is usually simpler, while an MoE Transformer can be more parameter-efficient at very large scale.\n\n---\n\n## In short\n\nA **Transformer** is the base architecture that uses attention to process sequences.\n\nAn **MoE** is a technique that uses multiple expert subnetworks and a router to decide which experts handle each token.\n\nThey are not mutually exclusive. Many MoE models are Transformers where some feed-forward layers have been replaced by routed expert layers.",
