      {
        "user": "What is a transformer (architecture)?",
        "assistant": "A **Transformer** is a neural network architecture designed to process sequences of data, such as text, code, audio, or images, using **attention mechanisms** rather than recurrence or convolution as its core operation.\n\nIt was introduced in the 2017 paper **“Attention Is All You Need”** and is the foundation of models like **GPT**, **BERT**, **T5**, and many modern large language models.\n\n## Core idea\n\nInstead of reading a sentence word by word like an RNN, a Transformer looks at all tokens in a sequence at once and learns which tokens should “pay attention” to which others.\n\nFor example, in:\n\n> “The animal didn’t cross the street because it was tired.”\n\nA Transformer can learn that **“it”** likely refers to **“the animal”**, not “the street.”\n\n## Main components\n\n### 1. Token embeddings\n\nInput text is split into tokens, and each token is converted into a vector representation.\n\nExample:\n\n> “The cat sat” → `[The] [cat] [sat]` → vectors\n\n### 2. Positional encoding\n\nBecause Transformers process tokens in parallel, they need a way to know token order.\n\nSo the model adds **positional information** to the token embeddings.\n\nThis helps it distinguish:\n\n> “dog bites man”\n\nfrom:\n\n> “man bites dog”\n\n### 3. Self-attention\n\nSelf-attention lets each token compare itself to every other token in the sequence.\n\nEach token produces three vectors:\n\n- **Query**\n- **Key**\n- **Value**\n\nAttention scores are computed by comparing queries and keys, then using those scores to weight the values.\n\nIn simplified form:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d}}\\right)V\n\\]\n\nThis allows the model to decide which tokens are most relevant to each other.\n\n### 4. Multi-head attention\n\nInstead of doing attention once, Transformers do it multiple times in parallel using **attention heads**.\n\nDifferent heads can learn different relationships, such as:\n\n- grammar\n- subject-verb agreement\n- coreference\n- long-range dependencies\n- semantic similarity\n\n### 5. Feed-forward networks\n\nAfter attention, each token representation passes through a small neural network, usually called a **feed-forward layer** or **MLP**.\n\nThis helps transform and refine the learned representations.\n\n### 6. Residual connections and layer normalization\n\nTransformers use:\n\n- **residual connections**, which help preserve information and improve training\n- **layer normalization**, which stabilizes learning\n\nThese make very deep Transformer models easier to train.\n\n## Encoder-decoder structure\n\nThe original Transformer had two main parts:\n\n### Encoder\n\nThe encoder reads and represents the input sequence.\n\nUsed in models like:\n\n- **BERT**\n- text classifiers\n- embedding models\n\n### Decoder\n\nThe decoder generates output tokens one at a time.\n\nUsed in models like:\n\n- **GPT**\n- many language models\n\n### Encoder-decoder\n\nSome models use both encoder and decoder.\n\nUsed in models like:\n\n- **T5**\n- original machine translation Transformers\n\nExample task:\n\n> English sentence → Encoder → Decoder → French sentence\n\n## Why Transformers are important\n\nTransformers became dominant because they:\n\n- handle long-range dependencies well\n- train efficiently in parallel\n- scale extremely well with data and compute\n- work across many domains, including text, images, audio, and code\n\n## In short\n\nA **Transformer** is a deep learning architecture based on **self-attention** that processes sequences by learning relationships between all tokens in parallel. It is the core architecture behind most modern large language models.",
