        "user": "How does \"transformer (architecture)\" differ from RNN (Recurrent Neural Network)?",
        "assistant": "A **Transformer architecture** differs from an **RNN** mainly in how it processes sequences and captures dependencies.\n\n| Aspect | Transformer | RNN |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Sequence processing** | Processes all token positions in parallel | Processes tokens sequentially, one step at a time |\n| **Core mechanism** | Multi-head self-attention | Recurrent hidden state |\n| **Memory of context** | Each token can directly attend to every other token | Context is passed through hidden states over time |\n| **Long-range dependencies** | Handles them well because attention can connect distant tokens directly | Can struggle with long-range dependencies due to vanishing/exploding gradients |\n| **Training efficiency** | Highly parallelizable, efficient on GPUs/TPUs | Less parallelizable because each step depends on the previous one |\n| **Position information** | Needs positional encodings or embeddings | Order is built in through sequential recurrence |\n| **Typical modern use** | Large language models, translation, vision transformers, multimodal models | Older sequence models, time-series models, some streaming applications |\n\nIn short: an **RNN reads a sequence step by step**, maintaining a hidden state, while a **Transformer processes the whole sequence in parallel** and uses **self-attention** to learn relationships between tokens. This parallelism and direct attention over positions are major reasons Transformers largely replaced RNNs in modern NLP.",
