        "user": "How does \"transformer (architecture)\" differ from MoE (Mixture of Experts)?",
        "assistant": "A **Transformer architecture** and **MoE (Mixture of Experts)** are different kinds of concepts.\n\nA **Transformer** is a full neural network architecture for sequence processing, built from:\n\n- multi-head self-attention\n- position-wise feed-forward layers\n- residual connections\n- layer normalization\n- parallel processing of sequence positions\n\nAn **MoE**, by contrast, is usually a **model scaling technique** or **layer design** where different inputs are routed to different “expert” subnetworks.\n\n| Aspect | Transformer | MoE |\n|---|---|---|\n| **What it is** | A neural network architecture | A conditional computation technique |\n| **Core mechanism** | Self-attention + feed-forward sublayers | Router/gating network selects expert networks |\n| **Purpose** | Model relationships among sequence positions | Increase model capacity efficiently |\n| **Sequence modeling** | Designed specifically to process sequences | Not specific to sequences |\n| **Typical use** | Language models, translation, vision, multimodal models | Often used inside large models, including Transformers |\n| **Computation** | Usually activates the same layers for every token | Activates only some experts per token/input |\n| **Relationship** | Can exist without MoE | Can be added to a Transformer |\n\nIn many modern systems, MoE is used **inside a Transformer**, often replacing or augmenting the standard feed-forward/MLP sublayer with multiple expert MLPs. A router decides which expert or experts handle each token.\n\nSo the key distinction is:\n\n> A **Transformer** is the overall architecture based on attention, while **MoE** is a way to make parts of a model sparse and expert-specialized.\n\nFor example:\n\n- **GPT-style dense Transformer**: every token uses the same feed-forward layers.\n- **MoE Transformer**: each token is routed to one or a few expert feed-forward layers.\n\nIn short, they are not direct alternatives. **MoE is often a component used within Transformer architectures to scale them more efficiently.**",
